UW Hospital ranked in top 50 in seven specialties by magazine

BYLINE: By BILL NOVAK The Capital Times bnovak@madison.com

SECTION: NEWS; Pg. WEB

LENGTH: 246 words


.University of Wisconsin Hospital and Clinics is ranked among the nation's best
hospitals in seven different specialities, according to the 2010 "America's Best
Hospitals" report from U.S. News and World Report.

The report released on Thursday ranked U.S. hospitals in 16 specialties.

UW Hospital has been ranked every year since 1993.

"As every member of our staff here knows, this hospital puts patient safety and
the quality of care at the center of our efforts," Donna Katen-Bahensky,
president and CEO of UW Hospital and Clinics, said in a news release from the UW
news service.

"I am happy to acknowledge these strong rankings and give credit to outstanding
physicans and staff," Katen-Bahensky said.

The publication ranks the top 50 hospitals in 16 specialties, after reviewing
4,852 hospitals. Only 152 of the hospitals scored high enough to be ranked in
any specialty.

The best ranking for UW Hospital was in kidney disorders at No. 28 out of 1,600
facilities analyzed.

UW Hospital was ranked No. 30 out of 984 facilities in the cancer category; No.
36 out of 1,500 in geriatrics; No. 39 out of 1,400 in ear, nose and throat; No.
40 out of 1,500 in urology; No. 43 out of 1,600 in orthopedics and No. 44 out of
1,600 in pulmonology.

The only other hospital in Wisconsin ranked in the top 50 is Froedtert Hospital
in Milwaukee, ranked No. 34 in gastroenterology, the UW news release said.

